        {
          "id": 52980,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Intravenous Diazepam</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 4-year-old boy named Ayan is brought to the emergency department after experiencing a seizure accompanied by a sudden fever spike to 105&deg;F. Upon examination, the child&#39;s vital signs are stable. There is no history of previous seizures, and no organic cause is identified. Based on these findings, a provisional diagnosis of febrile seizure is made. Rectal diazepam is administered, which successfully terminates the seizure. Considering the need to prevent future recurrences of similar febrile seizure episodes, which medication should be recommended?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3029545",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32732,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Oral Diazepam.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Based on the clinical features, it&rsquo;s a clearcut case of<strong> febrile seizures </strong>and as there is <strong>no any organic cause</strong>, <strong>anti-epileptic medications are not advised</strong>. Rectal diazepam or intra nasal midazolam is used. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Oral<strong> Diazepam </strong>is used intermittently as a<strong> prophylactic treatment </strong>to prevent the<strong> recurrence of febrile seizures </strong>during fever episodes. It is<strong> not used </strong>continuously but can be given at the<strong> onset of fever to reduce the likelihood of a seizure </strong>in children who are at <strong>high risk for recurrent febrile seizures</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Paracetamol </strong>is not used for the<strong> prophylaxis of febrile Seizures</strong>; they are used <strong>to control the fever</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Oral Paracetamol:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Paracetamol (also known as acetaminophen) is used to<strong> reduce fever </strong>but does <strong>not prevent the recurrence of febrile seizures</strong>, though it can be used to treat the fever in conjunction with other seizure prophylactics.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Intra Venous Paracetamol</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Intravenous paracetamol is an option for <strong>managing fever when oral administration is not feasible</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Intra Venous Diazepam:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Intravenous diazepam may be used in <strong>emergency situations to stop prolonged seizures </strong>but is not typically used for <strong>prevention of febrile seizures.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Drug of choice of<strong> febrile seizure </strong>is<strong> rectal diazepam or intra nasal midazolam</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Antipyretic medications, such as <strong>oral paracetamol, are commonly used to reduce fever </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: OP Ghai 9<sup>th</sup> Edition Page No- 554. </span></strong></span></span></p>",
