          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Febrile seizures are seizures that occur between the ages of 6 and 60 mo (peak 12-18 mo) with a temperature of 38&deg;C (100.4&deg;F) or higher, that are not the result of CNS infection.</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The parents of a 4-year-and-6-month-old child, who has recently been diagnosed with febrile seizures, are seeking clarification about the condition. They are particularly concerned about the age range for febrile seizures, noting that a cousin experienced similar episodes at the age of 3. What information should be provided to the parents regarding the common age range for febrile seizures?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3647912",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32734,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Febrile seizures are seizures that occur between the ages of 6 and 60 mo (peak 12-18 mo) with a temperature of 38&deg;C (100.4&deg;F) or higher, that are not the result of CNS infection.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;Febrile seizures typically occur in<strong> children between the ages of 6 months and 5 years (60 months), </strong>with a<strong> peak </strong>incidence between <strong>12 and 18 months</strong>. They are associated with <strong>fevers of 38&deg;C (100.4&deg;F) </strong>or higher and are<strong> not caused by an infection of the central nervous system</strong>, such as<strong> meningitis or encephalitis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Febrile seizures </strong>commonly occur between the<strong> ages of 6 and 60 months (peak between 12-18 months). </strong>It is <strong>relatively common and often benign</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: OP Ghai 9<sup>th</sup> Edition Page No- 554. </span></span></strong></p>",
