      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 53053,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Simple febrile seizure</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 53054,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Complex febrile seizures</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 53055,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">FIRES</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 53056,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Febrile status epilepticus</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 4-year-old child is brought to the hospital by his mother after experiencing a high-grade fever and a generalized tonic-clonic seizure lasting for 10 minutes. After the initial episode resolves, the child is admitted to the pediatric ward for observation. On the second day of admission, the child suffers another generalized tonic-clonic seizure after 24 hours, this time lasting for 14 minutes. The parents, who work as paramedical professionals, inquire whether these episodes represent simple or complex febrile seizures. Based on the provided information, what is the correct classification of the seizures?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3921967",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32735,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Simple febrile seizures</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Simple febrile seizures </strong>are generally short<strong> (less than 15 minutes) </strong>and <strong>do not recur </strong>within a<strong> 24-hour period</strong>. Associated generalized <strong>seizures </strong>with <strong>fever, typically in children aged 6 months to 5 years, without any neurological abnormalities.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B. Complex febrile seizures</strong> are characterized by one or more of the following: duration longer than <strong>15 minutes</strong>,<strong> recurrence within a 24-hour period</strong>, and<strong> focal features</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C. FIRES</strong> (Febrile Infection-Related Epilepsy Syndrome) is a <strong>rare epilepsy syndrome </strong>that does not apply to this situation.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Febrile status epilepticus</strong> would be a <strong>single seizure lasting for more than 30 minutes </strong>or<strong> multiple seizures </strong>during which the <strong>patient does not return to a normal level of consciousness between episodes</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Simple febrile seizures </strong>are brief, <strong>generalized seizures without focal features, </strong>typically lasting <strong>less than 15 minutes</strong>. Complex febrile seizures, while generally <strong>not indicative of an underlying epilepsy syndrome</strong>, may warrant closer monitoring and evaluation to rule out central nervous system infections or other etiologies.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: OP Ghai 9<sup>th</sup> Edition Page No- 554.&nbsp;</strong></span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 53053,
