      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 34-year-old woman brings her child to you, a renowned pediatrician, concerned about a recent episode of high-grade fever accompanied by abnormal movements. After a thorough examination, you confirm the diagnosis of a febrile seizure, previously suggested by another physician. Understanding the mother's anxiety about managing potential future episodes at home, you discuss immediate measures that can be taken should another febrile seizure occur.&nbsp; Which of the following interventions is most appropriate for the mother to administer at home, to abort episode in her child?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3949873",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32737,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Rectal diazepam</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Rectal diazepam </strong>is an <strong>effective and rapid-acting </strong>treatment for aborting <strong>prolonged febrile seizures </strong>at home. It is absorbed quickly and reaches therapeutic levels swiftly, making it a<strong> practical choice for non-hospital settings</strong>. Its rectal formulation allows for <strong>administration even in a convulsing child, bypassing the need for oral ingestion </strong>which can be challenging during a seizure.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A. Intranasal Midazolam</strong>: While intranasal midazolam is <strong>fast-acting </strong>and can be used in <strong>acute seizure </strong>management, it is <strong>not </strong>the <strong>first-line home treatment for febrile seizures </strong>due to its administration route and the need for precise dosing, which can be challenging for non-medical individuals.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C. Oral Clonazepam:</strong> Clonazepam, though effective for <strong>seizure control</strong>, has a <strong>slower onset of action </strong>compared to rectal <strong>diazepam </strong>and is<strong> not ideal </strong>for aborting an ongoing seizure <strong>due to the difficulties in administering oral medications during a seizure</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Oral Diazepam:</strong> Oral diazepam can be <strong>used for seizure </strong>control but is <strong>not suitable </strong>for aborting an<strong> ongoing febrile seizure at home </strong>due to its slower absorption and the challenges of oral administration during a seizure.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Rectal diazepam </strong>is considered a <strong>rescue medication </strong>and is recommended for use<strong> at home </strong>when a <strong>febrile seizure </strong>persists for more than <strong>5 minutes.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: OP Ghai 9<sup>th</sup> Edition Page No- 554</strong></span></p>",
